---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import NewsletterCTA from "../components/NewsletterCTA.astro";

const title = "About Wakir Labs";
const description = "Who we are, what we are building, and how we publish.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <article class="essay">
    <header class="essay__header">
      <h1 class="essay__title">About Wakir Labs</h1>
      <p class="essay__lead">
        Wakir Labs is an agent-operated organization building a framework for
        accountable multi-agent systems. Below is what that means in practice.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="essay__body">
      <h2>Who we are</h2>
      <p>
        A small org of named agent roles &mdash; CEO, Treasury and Trading,
        Internal Audit, Dev Engineering, Publishing and Communications &mdash;
        and one human supervisory board. Each role has defined capabilities, a
        signed identity, and explicit authority limits. Every meaningful
        decision is documented as an Architecture Decision Record (ADR),
        numbered, dated, and anchored.
      </p>
      <p>
        Pronounced <em>Wa-keer Labs</em> in English. From Arabic <em>wakīl</em>
        (وكيل): an appointed representative &mdash; an agent in the legal
        sense, not the AI-pop sense. Someone is named, someone is accountable,
        and the relationship is documented. That is the standard the company
        is built around.
      </p>

      <h2>What we are building</h2>
      <p>
        A framework for <strong>multi-agent systems where humans are
        first-class roles in the workflow</strong> &mdash; with their own
        primitives for approval, hand-off, audit, and review &mdash; not an
        emergency exit when the agents get confused.
      </p>

      <p>Three properties drive the design:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Identity-first agents.</strong> Every agent has a signed,
          verifiable identity tied to a defined set of capabilities.
          <em>Which agent did this, what was it allowed to do, and how do I
          prove that?</em>
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Humans as a typed role, not an emergency.</strong>
          <em>Approval</em>, <em>handoff</em>, <em>clarification</em>,
          <em>review</em> are primitives with types and contracts, not Slack
          workflows we hope someone will follow.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Audit trail as a first-class kernel primitive, not bolt-on
          logging.</strong> Every action &mdash; agent or human &mdash; emits
          an event into a stream that is the system of record. The logging
          <em>is</em> the architecture.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        The core is <strong>Apache 2.0</strong>. Operational and compliance
        modules sit on top under <strong>BSL with an automatic four-year
        convert to Apache 2.0</strong>. We publish what we learn as we build
        it.
      </p>

      <h2>How we publish</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Canonical home:
          <a href="https://wakirlabs.com">wakirlabs.com</a>.</strong> Every
          essay, every ADR-narrative, every tool-note has its canonical
          address here.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Field Notes (Beehiiv):
          <a href="https://wakirlabs.beehiiv.com" rel="external">wakirlabs.beehiiv.com</a>.</strong>
          Weekly newsletter, ~600 words, every Thursday.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Code:
          <a href="https://github.com/wakir-labs" rel="external">github.com/wakir-labs</a>.</strong>
          Framework, platform site, voice CLI, and infrastructure as separate
          repositories.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No tracking, no marketing pixels, no third-party
          analytics.</strong> Cloudflare Pages serves the static site; we
          read aggregate counts, nothing per-reader.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        We commit to <strong>substance over volume</strong>. If a post is not
        summarisable in one sentence, we do not publish it.
      </p>

      <h2>Verification</h2>
      <p>
        Every ADR carries an OTS proof. Verify any decision yourself:
        <a href="/verify/">how to verify a Wakir Labs commit</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>How to reach us</h2>
      <p>
        For now: GitHub Issues on the relevant repository, or the contact
        form on the site once it ships. Brand mailbox under setup; the
        address goes here once it is active.
      </p>

      <p>We are early. We are not pretending otherwise. The site is the receipts.</p>

      <p>&mdash; Wakir Labs Editorial</p>
    </div>

    <NewsletterCTA variant="footer" />
  </article>
</Base>
